Single-source images
----field----
field: {00E1D306-96BD-4B32-85B4-CD63C53CC6C1}
name: Abstract
key: abstract
content-length: 495

<p>The bane of any visually-centric site is images. With statically driven websites (or even other CMS frameworks) you have to create and maintain seperate thumbnails for each usage and size. Not so with Sitecore - you can upload a single, high-resolution version of the image and it is automatically scaled and cached on the server for each instance. You get all the advantages of maintaining a single image, as well as the advantages of scaled and properly sized images for your end users.</p>
----field----
field: {5A5684BB-8B54-44F6-ABCC-2BADA05ADA5D}
name: Body
key: body
content-length: 14006

<p>All Sitecore images are stored in the Media Library. These assets share many characteristics of Sitecore content items: they can be versioned, have metadata, permissions, etc. The primary difference is that media items don't have layouts applied, and exists as links (i.e. PDFs) or embedded in a document (i.e. images/video).</p>
<p>Images are uploaded to the Media Library in a directory structure. This structure can be secured with permissions, and additionally, when used in an image field, restricted as to use (i.e. a logo field may only get images from the logo directory).</p>
<p>Images can be placed on a page through one of two ways;</p>
<ul>
 <li>As an image within a Rich-Text field </li>
 <li>Using the image field.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Rich-Text</h3>
<p>When an image is placed in a Rich-Text field, a user has the ability to modify the height and width. Sitecore will scale down the image <em>for use in this instance</em> and cache the result. The source image (and any other usages of that image) remain unaffected.</p>
