<p> </p>
<p>When you add an image, Sitecore stores the reference as a link to the item ID - rather than the path. This is to ensure that if the image changes location in the repository, the link will still correctly resolve on output, preventing broken links. Also note that the height and width are passed in both the img tag, as well as in the src attribute. The img width and height let the browser know what to expect (to properly build tables, etc.) and the h=61&amp;w=76 pass the height and width to the Sitecore media handler ASHX to serve up the image from cache with the appropriate width and height.</p>
<p>The end result is that only one image is stored in Sitecore, but it can be reused in many places with excellent performance due to the media handler resizing and caching each use.</p>
<h3>Image Fields</h3>
<p>Rich-Text allows users to add images, and the HTML editor allows height and width resizing. If you are using the image field, as a developer, you have even more variables to work with. Using the properties below, you have a great deal more control over image scaling, stretching, and language/version.</p>
<p>In C#, these are the main properties of the MediaUrlOptions class. In XSL, these are attributes on the &lt;sc:image&gt; element.</p>
